<raw><![CDATA[    Investing.com – The U.S. dollar was down against most of the other major currencies on Monday, amid low trading volume, as U.S. markets were closed for the Labor Day holiday.  During European morning trade, the greenback was up against the euro, with EUR/USD shedding 0.12% to hit 1.2880.Earlier in the day, data showed that investor confidence in the euro zone fell unexpectedly in September.The greenback was also up against the pound, with GBP/USD falling 0.30% to hit 1.5404.Earlier Monday, industry data showed that new car sales declined sharply in August, falling for the second consecutive month.But the U.S. dollar was down against the yen and Swiss franc, with USD/JPY shedding 0.15% to hit 84.21 and USD/CHF shedding 0.36% to hit 1.0127.On Tuesday, the Bank of Japan was expected to hold a monetary policy meeting, after which the central bank was to announce its interest rate decision.Meanwhile, the greenback was down against its Australian, New Zealand and Canadian counterparts, as AUD/USD gained 0.03% to hit 0.9168, NZD/USD advanced 0.29% to hit 0.7230, while USD/CAD fell 0.37% to hit 1.0349.The dollar index, which tracks the performance of the greenback versus a basket of six other major currencies, was up 0.05%.Markets in the U.S. and Canada remain closed for Labor Day.             ]]></raw>
